E.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5694,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5694/v-ix","reputation":607,"display_name":"V_ix"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1395240605,"creation_date":1395240605,"body":"<p>I have to add that the authors do not show <em>any<\/em> evidence for cell shrinkage. In fact, the word shrink is not mentioned even once in the article. Therefore the BBC article is not correct. To answer your question, all we know is that there is more fluid clearance; the authors <em>do not<\/em> show the mechanisms for this.  <\/p>\n","answer_id":15946,"question_id":10934,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/10934/do-brain-cells-shrink-during-rem-sleep-or-a-lucid-dream","last_activity_date":1395240605,"creation_date":1382050228,"answer_count":2,"title":"Do brain cells shrink during REM sleep or a lucid dream?","body":"<p>In <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-24567412\" rel=\"nofollow\">this BBC news article<\/a> a study shows that during sleep brain cells shrink to open up the gaps between neurons and allow fluid to wash the brain clean.  But do the cells shrink and undergo the whole procedure during REM sleep and lucid dreaming?<\/p>\n","question_id":10934,"tags":["neuroscience","physiology","brain","sleep","dreaming"],"score":2,"down_vote_count":1,"is_answered":true,"view_count":450,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1382058977},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b4548b0947c4424cae692a0d2badc8f9?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":5486,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5486/piret-avila","reputation":16,"display_name":"Piret Avila"},"closed_date":1415886759,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_