"One unit will inhibit the rate of reduction of cytochrome c by 50% in a coupled system, using xanthine and xanthine oxidase ...\"<\/p>\n\n<p>I don't think, there is a good way to convert ng's to units, since one measures either mass or enzymatic activity, and the correlation between them is not always consistent. Units should be much more reliable in terms of comparisons with other studies, if you are not considering your enzyme as, e.g., a nutritious substance.<\/p>\n","answer_id":15094,"question_id":15089,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1392634857},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5415a54cb3113662c8f9c1ea61767f49?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":5741,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5741/user5741","reputation":21,"display_name":"user5741"},"score":0,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"score":0,"post_id":15108,"edited":false,"creation_date":1392644569,"comment_id":20191,"body":"But: This is only valid for a certain batch, since the activity of protein preparations varies between batches. Thats why we have this units, which is not a very good thing. But better than nothing."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5415a54cb3113662c8f9c1ea61767f49?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":5741,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5741/user5741","reputation":21,"display_name":"user5741"},"score":1,"post_id":15108,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"edited":false,"creation