alue shouldn&#39;t affect the result in any way, as long as you multiple <i>all<\/i> values. Basically 1 means you <i>always<\/i> have that residue at that position. If you multiply by say 100, you can treat them as percentages. But yes, the implementations could vary depending on what you&#39;re feeding them to."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/v5upF.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3624,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3624/fileunderwater","reputation":10502,"display_name":"fileunderwater"},"score":3,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1395165691,"creation_date":1395133733,"body":"<p>So what you need is basically your data expressed as counts instead of proportions. Even if you do not have the matrix of counts as raw data, these proportions only needs to be multiplied by the total number of binding sites used in the study (e.g. the number of sequences that have been analysed) to get the counts (since proportion = count/total number of binding sites). You should have that information somewhere. <\/p>\n\n<p>@hello_there_andy: indeed there was this missing piece of information available to me, it came in the form of a variable called <strong>nsites<\/strong> which equates to the total number of DNA sites that the PWM was generated from.  <\/p>\n","answer_id":15906,"question_id":15898,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1395165691}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/15898/how-can-i-re-format-my-dna-motifs-position-weight-matrices","last_activity_date":1395165691,"creation_date":1395073064,"answer_count":1,"title":"How can I re-format my DNA motifs' position weight matrices?","body":"<p>I am working with a set of DNA motifs that are predicted as potential regulatory motifs (e.g. transcription factor binding sites).\nThe motifs belong to several species, and I wanted to cluster these motifs via their Position Weight Matrices (PWMs) (also known as PSSMs) to collapse similar motifs together into groups.<\/p>\n\n<p>There is a tool called MATLIGN (<a href=\"http://ekhidna.biocenter.helsinki.fi/poxo/matlign/help#p0\" rel=\"nofollow\">website here<\/a>) that does what I need, but their required format for the PWMs are different to what I have, they claim:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>\"Matrices must be in the frequency matrix format (only integer numbers\n  are acceptable)\"<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>The problem is that my PWM matrices do not have integer numbers but decimals instead. e.g.:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>     A        C        G        T\n1    0.000000 1.000000 0.000000 0.000000\n2    1.000000 0.000000 0.000000 0.000000\n3    0.000000 0.000000 1.000000 0.000000\n4    0.000000 0.421755 0.000000 0.578245\n5    0.289407 0.000000 0.282556 0.428038\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>In other words, instead of the decimal values I have in my matrix I need to have integer counts. Could anybody suggest what I can do? Would I need to create artificial \"pseudo-counts\"?<\/p>\n","question_id":15898,"tags":["dna","transcription","software","gene-regulation","transcription-factor"],"score":3,"accepted_answer_id":15906,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":67,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1395138421},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/ZR6SM.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5005,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5005/hello-there-andy","reputation":1616,"display_name":"hello_there_andy","accept_rate":69},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/79614cc5fcd376b95171a5c8f6354e8a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":5754,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5754/jarlemag","reputation":3075,"display_name":"jarlemag"},"score":2,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/ZR6SM.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5005,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5005/hello-there-a