or of the spider species is reduced/ the species do not face overcrowding. There has to be a selfish advantage to the spider."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/f0PGT.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3615,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3615/biogirl","reputation":3923,"display_name":"biogirl","accept_rate":89},"score":1,"post_id":15415,"edited":false,"creation_date":1393661469,"comment_id":20698,"body":"I also strongly recommend the book - The selfish gene by Richard Dawkins which explains the common concepts of evolutionary biology in an interesting way !"}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"score":4,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a13870e0f2891959411f77c5ec090b1a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":5874,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5874/iyengar","reputation":116,"display_name":"Iyengar"},"score":0,"post_id":15416,"edited":false,"creation_date":1393590497,"comment_id":20662,"body":"Wonderful ! What about my thought experiment ? Any answer/comment to that ? Thanks so much +1. @Chris"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"score":1,"post_id":15416,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a13870e0f2891959411f77c5ec090b1a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":5874,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5874/iyengar","reputation":116,"display_name":"Iyengar"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1393596646,"comment_id":20667,"body":"@lyengar: I expanded my answer."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1393596629,"creation_date":1393587868,"body":"<p>Too long for a comment:<\/p>\n\n<p>Evolution and mutation has nothing to do with intelligence and is not influenced by the cells itself. It happens by chance and if the mutation turns out to be beneficial (or at least not harmful for the moment) it will be a selection advantage. <\/p>\n\n<p>Something to think about: If a mutation in an enzyme which is responsible for Glucose metabolization allows bacteria to also metabolize another sugar (lets say Galactose) with the same enzyme, this will not change anything for the moment. If these cells are living in a substrate where glucose gets a limiting nutrient but which contains still a lot of galactose, these bacteria will have a growth advantage and overgrow the other strain. Eventually the strain, which can only metabolize glucose will disappear completely.<\/p>\n\n<p>Evolution is also a very gradual and slow process. So it is not <em>boom<\/em> suddenly birds appear on the sky, it is a process which took millions of to happen. All the things which allow birds to fly (hollow bones, feathers and so on) developed slowly.<\/p>\n\n<p>Genes do not know anything, since they have no consciousness. They are \"simply\" building blocks. They also don't solve any problems, they are only expressed, not more. \nIt is like you write, genes acquire mutations, which allows changes in function or morphology. As stated above: This is a slow and steady process with a lot of dead ends.<\/p>\n","answer_id":15416,"question_id":15415,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1393596629},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/889548c1e8387b3d381853dee5212cfd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3632,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3632/shigeta","reputation":22684,"display_name":"shigeta","accept_rate":86},"score":8,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"p