rties of the sound wave that enters your ear depending on the angle at which it fell on you outer ear.<\/p>\n","answer_id":15647,"question_id":15553,"up_vote_count":3},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5c0cf46c3426ba3b0eebe6163d1aa130?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6003,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6003/dan-horvat","reputation":304,"display_name":"Dan Horvat"},"score":-1,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/de2c4fd753821f85c74d886aa17410de?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":107,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/107/kmm","reputation":8486,"display_name":"kmm"},"score":0,"post_id":15655,"edited":false,"creation_date":1394632997,"comment_id":21124,"body":"Can you provide citations to support your assertions? What makes you certain that the ear in humans has not been subject to selection? I&#39;m not suggesting that it has, but I would like to know if there is evidence to the contrary."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5c0cf46c3426ba3b0eebe6163d1aa130?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6003,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6003/dan-horvat","reputation":304,"display_name":"Dan Horvat"},"score":0,"post_id":15655,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/de2c4fd753821f85c74d886aa17410de?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":107,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/107/kmm","reputation":8486,"display_name":"kmm"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1394637652,"comment_id":21128,"body":"Just take a look at the ear(s) of any great ape. Clearly ear hasn&#39;t been changed much within our species and the development took part much earlier in our lineage."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/de2c4fd753821f85c74d886aa17410de?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1