tem of lipoproteins (LDL, VLDL etc.) and pretty much can end up anywhere, including fat cells (adipocytes) or they can be metabolised as fuel molecules<\/p>\n\n<p>So, because of that initial digestive step I would say that a single intact dietary fat molecule cannot end up as a body component directly, but complete metabolism of the components of the fat molecule is not necessary for these to contribute to body fat.<\/p>\n","answer_id":15628,"question_id":15618,"up_vote_count":6},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5c0cf46c3426ba3b0eebe6163d1aa130?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6003,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6003/dan-horvat","reputation":304,"display_name":"Dan Horvat"},"score":0,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1394560493,"creation_date":1394560493,"body":"<p>Fat is digested just like any other food you consume, and eventually the energy you do not expend ends up as an energy reserve in shape of fat cells.<\/p>\n\n<p>So, the second statement is right.<\/p>\n","answer_id":15660,"question_id":15618,"up_vote_count":0}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/15618/does-fat-on-our-heart-come-from-the-fat-that-we-eat","last_activity_date":1394560493,"creation_date":1394433144,"answer_count":2,"title":"Does fat on our heart come from the fat that we eat?","body":"<p>If we eat fat:<\/p>\n\n<p>Does the fat go into heart, arteries and fat cells.<\/p>\n\n<p>OR<\/p>\n\n<p>Is the fat digested, following which our body creates fat that goes into heart, arteries and fat cells.<\/p>\n\n<p>Which one is right?<\/p>\n","question_id":15618,"tags":["fatty-acid-synthase"],"score":0,"accepted_answer_id":15628,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":45,"up_vote_count":0,"last_edit_date":1394455782},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f30fbd436650e66fd9632b770d6ac920?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":324,"link":"http://b